<exercise checkit-seed="0006" checkit-slug="SQ3" checkit-title="Partial sum sequence">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    Consider the partial sum sequence <m>\displaystyle A_n=\left(3\right)+\left(\frac{9}{4}\right)+\left(\frac{27}{16}\right)+\cdots+\left(3\cdot \left( \frac{3}{4}\right)^n \right).</m>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Find a closed form for <m>A_n</m>.</li>
                        <li>Does <m>\{A_n\}</m> converge?  If so, to what value?</li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Consider the partial sum sequence <m>\displaystyle B_n=\sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{1}{5 \, i + 3}-\frac{1}{5 \, i + 8} \right).</m>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Find a closed form for <m>B_n</m>.</li>
                        <li>Does <m>\{B_n\}</m> converge?  If so, to what value?</li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
                
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle A_n=3\cdot\frac{1-\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{n+1} }{1- \left(\frac{3}{4}\right) }</m>.</li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty} 3\cdot\frac{1-\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^{n+1} }{1- \left(\frac{3}{4}\right) } </m> converges to <m>12</m>.                
                        </li>            
                    </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle B_n=\frac{1}{8}-\frac{1}{5 \, n + 8}</m>.</li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{1}{8}-\frac{1}{5 \, n + 8} </m> converges to <m>\frac{1}{8}</m>.                
                        </li>            
                    </ol>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
